  <subsection xml:id="how-to-solve-part-b-1">
            <title>How to Solve Part B</title>
          
                <p>To calculate <c>basicGapWidth</c> we need to find the number of spaces left after the characters fill the <c>formattedLen</c> and divide that
                    by the number of gaps between words.  We can use <c>totalLetters</c> (written in part A) to get the total number of characters for all the strings in <c>wordList</c>.
                    The number of gaps between words is the number of words in <c>wordList</c> minus 1.  The <c>basicGapWidth</c> is the number of spaces left divided by the number of gaps between words.  Remember that if we do an integer division any fractional part will be thrown away, which is what we want to happen in this case.</p>
                <p>For example, if <c>formattedLen</c> is 20 and <c>wordList</c> is [“AP”, “COMP”, “SCI”, “ROCKS”] then the number of spaces left is 20 - 14 = 6 and the number of gaps is 4 - 1 = 3.  The result is 6 / 3 = 2.</p>
                <p>If <c>formattedLen</c> is 20 and <c>wordList</c> is [“GREEN”, “EGGS”, “AND”, “HAM”] then the number of spaces left is 20 - 15 = 5 and the number of gaps is 4 - 1 = 3 so 5 / 3 = 1.  There will be two extra spaces left over.</p>
                <p>If <c>formattedLen</c> is 20 and <c>wordList</c> is [“BEACH”, “BALL”] then the number of spaces left is 20 - 9 = 11 and the number of gaps is 2 - 1 = 1 so 11 / 1 = 11.</p>
           
            

